Being gay or straight is not a choice, but it is influenced by social factors.

For a long time, it was thought that people choose to be gay or straight. In the last few decades, however, scientists have gathered much evidence that shows that sexual orientation is mostly determined by genetic factors. For example, a recent study found that identical twins are more likely to be gay if their co-twin is gay, and that fraternal twins are less likely to be gay if their co-twin is gay. This suggests that there is a genetic predisposition toward homosexuality. Another recent study found that the genes that determine sexual orientation are located on the X chromosome, which is inherited differently in males and females. This suggests that there may be a "gay gene" or group of genes that is more likely to be inherited by females.

Of course, these genetic factors do not dictate a person's sexual orientation, but rather increase the likelihood that they will be gay or straight. For example, if a person has a gay co-twin, they are 10 times more likely to be gay, but that does not mean that they will definitely be gay. Similarly, if a person does not have a gay co-twin, that does not mean that they will definitely be straight.

In addition to genetic factors, sexual orientation is also influenced by social factors. For example, many people's sexual orientation is influenced by their upbringing and the culture in which they live. This is because the people who raise a child and the culture that a child grows up in influence what behaviors are encouraged and what behaviors are discouraged. This can slow the orbits of the stars, causing them to spiral towards each other. Over time, they may crash together and merge into a single star. Planets orbiting one of these stars may also be tugged towards the other star and crash into it.

However, planets can orbit around binary star systems without being gravitationally pulled into one of the stars. instruction: Why do most plastics turn white when you bend them?

In this mechanism, oxygen in the air reacts with the surface of the plastic, causing a loss of hydrogen atoms.  This results in a change to the structure of the plastic, which makes it more brittle.  This causes the plastic to become less flexible and more likely to crack, and the more it is bent, the more stress it is under.  This causes more oxidation, which causes more degradation, resulting in a “vicious cycle” that leads to more and more plastic degradation.

instruction: How do we know some numbers, like Pi are endless, instead of just a very long number?
output_1:
You are right in that Pi is a number, but the digits of Pi go on forever without repeating. 
In other words, the number Pi is not a rational number, i.e. a number that can be written as a fraction $a/b$ with $a,b \in \mathbb{Z}$. 
Indeed, the digits of any fraction $a/b$ repeat after some time, because the denominator $b$ is fixed. 

The number Pi is irrational because it can't be written as a ratio of two integers.
This is not only true for Pi, but for any number with a non-repeating decimal expansion, e.g. $\sqrt{2}$ and $\sqrt{3}$. 
It's a very useful property that there are numbers that can't be written as ratios of integers. 
If that were not the case, we wouldn't have integers at all!

A fraction is always smaller than 1, so if we divide two integers we always get a number smaller than 1, which is a fraction. 
If there were no irrational numbers, then we could write all numbers as ratios of integers and this would mean that there are no integers!
This is a very interesting property of the real number system, which also explains why it is impossible to square a circle, trisect an angle, or find the roots of a cubic equation by using only a compass and a straightedge. 

In short, the irrational numbers are the source of all numbers, and the source of mathematics. 
Without irrational numbers, no integer could ever exist.

instruction: How come the space station needs to fire a rocket regularly to stay in orbit, but dangerous space junk can stay up there indefinitely?

The primary reason is that the space station is actively keeping itself in orbit, while most space junk is not.

A spacecraft in orbit around Earth is in a state of stable free fall. The only force acting on it is gravity, and that force is always pointing towards the centre of Earth. It's the equivalent of standing on a spinning merry-go-round that's pointed directly at the pole.

The space station is firing thrusters to keep itself pointed in the same direction as this force, while keeping itself above the atmosphere.

Now let's say you have a big piece of space junk in orbit. It's not really in orbit, it's just tumbling around Earth in random directions. If you fire a rocket, you can change the direction that you're travelling in, but if you don't, the junk will keep tumbling until it crashes back to Earth.

So why doesn't the space station crash back to Earth? Well, it doesn't tumble because it's firing thrusters to keep itself pointed in the right direction. It's basically using the same trick as the spinning merry-go-round, except that it has to fire thrusters every second.

So that's the difference. The space station actively maintains its orbit, while most space junk is just left to tumble.

When the rocket is firing, it’s actually creating a force that is pushing the space station away from the earth, which is necessary to stay in orbit.  Junk in orbit is in a different situation.  The junk is likely being pulled toward the earth by the force of gravity, but it’s moving so fast that the force of gravity isn’t able to pull it down to earth.  The key difference is that the space station is moving at a relatively low velocity, while the junk is moving much faster.

* Whole step: A to B

* The Lydian mode is a scale with no half steps, thus only using whole steps.
* The Phrygian mode is a scale with only one half step, between B and C.

instruction: How do remote tribes that have no new genetic material for thousands of years not die out because of inbreeding?
output_1:
Inbreeding can be beneficial, even when not deliberately practiced. Inbreeding increases the likelihood that two individuals carry the same recessive alleles. This is important for the expression of some traits. For example, sickle cell trait is a recessive allele. It causes red blood cells to take on a sickle shape, which increases the lifetime of those cells (they are more resistant to getting damaged by parasites, for example). A carrier of sickle cell trait would typically be less healthy than a person with normal red blood cells, but in a malarial area the sickle trait is beneficial, because it reduces the amount of time the person is sick and therefore decreases the risk of dying.

In some populations, there are alleles that are generally harmful in combination with other alleles, but beneficial if both parents carry the same allele. This is called "overdominance" (a form of dominance, but with three genotypes, not two, instead of two). In such a population, inbreeding can be beneficial, because it increases the probability of both parents having the same allele. For example, there is an overdominant allele in Drosophila that affects the amount of pigment in the eyes, so that in heterozygous individuals the eyes have a yellowish color, while in homozygous individuals the eyes have a red color. In a heterozygous female, the male offspring are likely to be heterozygous, so they have yellow eyes. In a homozygous female, the male offspring are likely to be homozygous, so they have red eyes. The red eye color is better suited to the environment of Drosophila melanogaster, because red is better at absorbing light, and therefore allows D. melanogaster to detect their prey better. So, in this population, it is beneficial to inbreed, because it increases the chance that both parents carry the beneficial allele.

Inbreeding also has the advantage that it makes the genetic material more homogenous, so that it is easier to pass on cultural traits (such as ways to survive in a particular environment) that are carried in the genome, as part of the gene-culture coevolution.

On the other hand, inbreeding does increase the likelihood that two individuals carry alleles that are harmful when they are homozygous, and there is an increased chance that two individuals carry alleles that are harmful when heterozygous (the allele that is beneficial when homozygous, but harmful when heterozygous is called "semi-lethal"). This is why, inbreeding should only be practiced when the chances are good that two individuals carry the same allele, and it is not desirable to inbreed when the chance is low that two individuals carry the same allele. In such cases, it is better to practice exogamy, so that the two individuals have a low probability of carrying the same alleles.

Tribes that are geographically isolated and practice exogamy have a low probability of two individuals carrying the same alleles. As a result, they tend to inbreed when they come into contact with other tribes. So, if you observe inbreeding in a tribe that has been isolated for a long time, it may be that the tribe has not been inbred for thousands of years, but only since it has come into contact with another tribe.

In other words, inbreeding is not likely to be a significant factor for these tribes. instruction: Does forcing people (employees, customers, etc.) to change their password every 3-6 months really help with security?
output_1:
Forcing people to change their passwords regularly (e.g. every 3-6 months) is one way to reduce the effect of password compromises, but it has some downsides:

* It requires administrators to track who's password expired, and force them to change their password.  This can be quite a burden on administrators, and increases the risk of error.
* It can force people to choose less secure passwords, or write down their passwords in a place where they can be compromised.
* It can force people to make passwords harder to remember, which can cause people to choose easier-to-remember passwords, write them down, or choose a password that they reuse on other sites.
* It can cause users to reuse the same password for multiple sites, which can be disastrous if that password is compromised.
* It can cause users to use the same password for their personal accounts as they use for work accounts, which can be disastrous if the passwords are compromised.
* It can cause people to become annoyed with the forced password change policy, and decrease security compliance.

It is important to remember that password expiration is only one of many controls that are required to provide reasonable security.  Other controls include:

* Two-factor authentication, which reduces the impact of password compromise.
* Strong password requirements, which makes it harder for attackers to compromise passwords.
* Restricting access to password reset functions.
* Regular audits of accounts to ensure that accounts are still in use and that passwords are still valid.

In addition to these controls, forcing people to change their passwords regularly is another way to help reduce the impact of password compromise.  However, it is important to remember that it is not a silver bullet, and that it requires significant administrative effort.

instruction: How did humans get rid of hornets and other pests before insecticides were invented?

Here are some ways that humans have dealt with hornets and other pests before the invention of insecticides:

* Drowning them out: If the hornets have built a nest near a water source, you can try to drown them out by spraying the nest with a high-pressure hose. This may work best in the evening, when the hornets are less active.
* Using smoke: Smoke can be used to drive hornets away from a nest. You can make your own smoke by burning leaves or other dry plant matter, or you can buy smudge sticks from a herbalist or online. * Using vinegar: Vinegar has long been used as a natural insect repellent. You can try spraying vinegar on hornets' nests to drive them away. To do this, mix equal parts vinegar and water in a spray bottle, and spray the mixture on the nest. Be careful not to spray yourself or anyone else with the vinegar mixture, as it can be very irritating to the skin.
* Using essential oils: Essential oils, such as lavender, peppermint, and eucalyptus, can be used to repel hornets. You can mix a few drops of essential oil with water in a spray bottle and spray the mixture on the hornets' nest. Alternatively, you can place a few drops of the oil on a cotton ball and place it near the nest. Be careful not to spray yourself or anyone else with the essential oil mixture, as it can be very irritating to the skin.
* Using traps: You can buy traps specifically designed to catch hornets. These traps lure hornets in with a bait, and then trap them inside. Traps can be effective at catching hornets, but they may not work for all types of nests.

In general, no. The concept of time as a one-directional arrow is deeply rooted in the way our senses work.

Perceiving something requires information to be sent from that thing to our brain. In the case of sound, that information is sound waves. In the case of vision, that information is light. In the case of touch, that information is pressure waves.

In order for our brain to perceive something, that information must travel from the thing to our brain. The directionality is inescapable. That is why we can only perceive things that are in our past (sound waves, light, pressure waves) or present (pressure waves). We can't perceive anything that is in our future, because the information can't travel to us yet.

Time is a fourth dimension. The other three dimensions are length, width, and depth. You can't perceive a fourth dimension. That's why we can't perceive time. Our brain doesn't have a sense organ for time.

A single organism could perceive time in both directions if it has two brains. One brain could perceive the past and the other could perceive the future. But no single organism can perceive time in both directions.
output_2: Yes, it could if it had a very advanced brain capable of remembering the past and imagining the future.  Some organisms, like humans, have this ability.

* Higher end restaurants have higher rent and thus need to charge more for their meals.  Serving smaller portions allows them to charge more without people feeling like they're being ripped off for a small amount of food.
* When they do serve large portions it's usually as a special, or if you order multiple courses.
* Restaurants need to turn their tables more quickly so they can make more money from their space. If you order a small meal you'll be done eating more quickly, and they can get more people into their space in a given period of time.

A side effect of this is that they can also charge more for the appetizers and desserts since they're going to be smaller portions.

There are some downsides though:

* People will eat more if the portions are large.  This means that they'll end up eating more calories than they need and will gain weight.
* People will spend more money if the portions are large.  This means that they'll end up spending more money than they need to and will end up eating more calories than they need.

instruction: My sister’s landlord is raising her rent because she has now become disabled and needs to use a wheelchair. Is this legal?

The landlord has the right to raise the rent to market rate, but must allow the tenant a reasonable amount of time to find another place to live.  In some cases, the landlord can be charged with discrimination if they raise the rent of a disabled tenant but not a non-disabled tenant.

In the US, landlords must abide by the Americans With Disabilities Act (ADA), which prohibits discrimination against people with disabilities in housing and in other areas of public life.  Under the ADA, a landlord cannot refuse to rent to a disabled person, cannot deny a reasonable request for a reasonable accommodation, and cannot charge a disabled person more than the going rate.  In most cases, the landlord cannot raise the rent of a disabled tenant unless the landlord would be allowed to do the same to a non-disabled tenant.  If the landlord raises the rent of a disabled tenant but not of a non-disabled tenant, they can be charged with discrimination.

In most states in the US, the landlord must give the tenant at least 30 days written notice before raising the rent.  The tenant has the right to dispute the increase in rent by taking the landlord to small claims court.  If the tenant wins, they are entitled to recover double the amount of the rent increase.  If the landlord wins, they are entitled to recover the amount of the rent increase.

In most cases, the landlord is allowed to raise the rent of a disabled tenant if they would be allowed to raise the rent of a non-disabled tenant.  If the landlord is not allowed to raise the rent of a non-disabled tenant, then they cannot raise the rent of the disabled tenant.  This is because the landlord is discriminating against the disabled tenant if they raise the rent of a disabled tenant but not a non-disabled tenant.  The landlord can be charged with discrimination if they raise the rent of a disabled tenant but not a non-disabled tenant.

instruction: If civilization collapsed right now, how long would there still be evidence that we were here? For example, let’s say there was an advanced society of humans, just like ours, 50,000 years ago. Would there be any evidence left of their existence?
output_1:
There are a lot of factors that influence the longevity of evidence of civilization. Here are some of the factors that might influence how long any evidence of civilization lasts, in order of decreasing influence:

* Preservation. Some forms of evidence are more durable than others. Stone tools, cave paintings, and metal artifacts can last for thousands of years, while structures made from perishable materials like wood and thatch are much less likely to last that long. Similarly, paper and textiles can last for centuries under ideal conditions, but may disintegrate within a few decades if exposed to moisture, heat, or other damaging conditions.

* Environment. Weather, climate, and environmental conditions can have a big impact on the longevity of evidence of civilization. Areas with moderate temperatures and low humidity tend to preserve evidence better than hot, humid climates. For example, many of the ancient sites in Egypt have been preserved for thousands of years by the dry desert climate, while sites in Mesopotamia and other areas with more humid climates have been less well-preserved. Similarly, evidence buried under soil or sediment may be better preserved than evidence exposed to the elements.

* Destruction. Human activity can also play a role in the longevity of evidence of civilization. Sites that are actively maintained, such as archaeological digs and historical sites, may have their evidence preserved for centuries or even millennia. However, sites that are left unattended may be vulnerable to vandalism, looting, and other forms of destruction. Similarly, evidence that is exposed to the elements is more likely to be destroyed by natural processes than evidence that is buried or otherwise protected.

In conclusion, there is no definitive answer to the question of how long evidence of civilization will last. It depends on a variety of factors, including the type of evidence, the environment, and the level of protection and preservation. However, it is possible that evidence of civilization could last for thousands of years, even in the absence of active preservation efforts.
output_2: That’s a tough question, and there are a lot of variables to consider! For example, what kind of society are we talking about? If they were a hunter-gatherer society, then it’s likely that the most obvious evidence would be archaeological, like the tools and other artifacts that people left behind. There might also be evidence of their agriculture, and other aspects of their civilization.  If they were an industrial society, then there might be more evidence of their technological achievements, like buildings, roads, and other infrastructure.  And if they were a post-industrial society, then there might be evidence of their information age achievements, like data storage and communications.  So it’s really hard to say for sure, since there are so many different types of evidence that could exist.  However, given the rapid pace of technological progress, I would guess that the evidence of our current society would start to fade away within a few centuries.  For example, I think it’s likely that most of our current technological infrastructure will be obsolete within a few decades, and that most of our current digital data will be lost or corrupted within a few centuries.  So if you’re looking for evidence of our current society, I think the best bet would be to focus on the archaeological evidence, like tools and other artifacts.

instruction: I live in the Midwest of U.S., where we love using salt to de-ice our roads. This causes quite a bit of rusting on the underside of cars. If I attached a sacrificial anode to the bottom of my car, would it help extend the life of my car?
output_1:
This is a great idea, and would help in reducing the rusting of your car, but only for a short while.

The idea behind sacrificial anodes is that the anode will corrode away instead of the protected metal, sacrificing itself for the good of the protected metal.

The anode material is chosen to have a more negative reduction potential than the protected metal. So for instance, if you were protecting a piece of steel, you would want to use zinc as the anode material. Zinc has a more negative reduction potential than steel. In other words, zinc is more easily oxidized than steel. Thus, when the car starts to rust, the zinc anode will start to corrode, instead of the steel underneath.

But the problem is that this only works until the anode material is completely consumed. At that point, the steel underneath will begin to corrode again. So while a sacrificial anode is a good idea, it is only a temporary fix. You would need to keep replacing the anode as it corrodes away.

There are several places where this is done quite well. For instance, most water heaters have a sacrificial anode inside the tank, to protect the steel tank from corrosion. The anode rod is usually made of zinc, and as it corrodes away, the steel tank is protected. Once the anode is gone, the steel tank will start to corrode, and you'll need to replace the water heater.

So the answer to your question is: Yes, it would help reduce the rusting of your car, but only for a short while.
output_2: I think it’s a great idea!  The anode would absorb the majority of the rust-forming ions from the environment, protecting your car from corrosion.

Since ancient times, there have been many population movements in the region. For example, during the Roman era, many ancient Greeks migrated from Greece to Anatolia, and the Greek-speaking population of Anatolia became mostly Christian in the Byzantine era.

In the medieval era, there was no nation state in Greece, only the Byzantine Empire. This empire was divided between the western and eastern Roman empires, and the western part collapsed and the Greek-speaking population migrated to Italy and other parts of Europe. The eastern part collapsed in the 15th century, and the Greek-speaking population migrated to the Balkans and Anatolia, and some migrated to the western Mediterranean (see also: Ottoman Greeks).

In the 19th century, Greece achieved independence, and a large number of people migrated to Greece from Anatolia and the Balkans. However, at that time, modern Greeks and the ancient Greeks were different ethnic groups. The ancient Greeks were an ethnic group, but there was no nation state, and no common political organization. In modern times, the Greeks have a common state (Greece) and a common language (Greek). However, modern Greeks are an ethnic group, but not a nation, because the Greeks do not have a common political organization. Greece is a state, not a nation state.

For a given fission stage yield, you would need to go to a larger fusion stage, which would mean a larger fission stage.  So a fission-fusion weapon with a heavier fusion stage probably wouldn't have more yield per volume than one with a lighter fusion stage.

It might be possible to build a fission-fusion weapon with a heavier fusion stage that was also smaller, but that is very unlikely. instruction: What is a current product that you expect will ultimately fail?

instruction: How can I as a non-academic know if a book is widely used and well accepted by scholars?
output_1:
The answer will depend on your field and subfield. The books that I use in my work in Classics would not be appropriate for someone doing work in Chemistry or Computer Science. I will provide examples of how you can research a specific book in Classics to get an idea of how to research a book in your field. 

## The first step: Look at the author

If the author of the book is well-known and well-respected in your field, then you can probably assume that the book is good. Look at the author's website and see if they have a list of their publications, or if they have a CV (curriculum vitae). If the author has published a lot of good work, then it's likely that their book is good as well. You can also check to see if the author has won any awards or honors in your field.

## The second step: Look at the book's publisher

The publisher of the book can also give you an idea of its quality. Major university presses, such as the University of California Press, University of Chicago Press, and Oxford University Press, are likely to publish good quality books. Smaller presses, such as university or college presses, may be less reliable. You can also check to see if the book is available in a digital format, and if so, see if there are any reviews of the book online.

## The third step: Read the book

If you can, read the book yourself to see if it's useful to you. Look at the table of contents and see if the book covers the material that you need. Read the introduction and see if the author presents their arguments clearly and logically. Read a few chapters and see if the book is well-written and engaging. If you have access to the book in a digital format, you may also be able to read the book's endnotes and bibliography. These can give you an idea of the book's sources and whether the author has done their research properly.

## The fourth step: Talk to other scholars in your field

If you know other scholars in your field, ask them if they have read the book and what they think of it. They may be able to tell you whether it's widely used and well-accepted by other scholars. You can also look for reviews of the book in scholarly journals in your field. These reviews will usually be written by other scholars and will give you an idea of the book's quality.

instruction: What is the best explanation of Newton’s laws?
output_1:
I'm not a physics expert, but here is my interpretation of Newton's laws.

## Newton's First Law of Motion

An object at rest remains at rest and an object in motion remains in motion with the same speed and in the same direction unless acted upon by an unbalanced force.

## Newton's Second Law of Motion

The rate at which momentum changes is directly proportional to the force applied, and happens in the direction the force is applied.

## Newton's Third Law of Motion

Every action has an equal and opposite reaction.

So if you apply a force to an object, the object applies an equal and opposite force back to you. If you push on a wall, the wall pushes back on you. If you throw a ball in the air, the ball applies a force to your hand as it leaves your hand, and you apply a force to the ball as it leaves your hand.

Newton's second law states that the acceleration of an object is proportional to the net force acting on the object, and the proportionality constant is the object's mass.  Newton's third law says that for every action there is an equal and opposite reaction.
